Aggregate functions: collapsing many rows into one.

An aggregate function takes a set of rows and returns a single value. The five standard aggregates cover almost everything. Count tells you how many. Sum gives a total. Average gives the arithmetic mean. Min gives the smallest value, and max gives the largest.

When you call an aggregate without a group by, the whole table is treated as one group, and you get back a single-row result. So a count over the whole orders table tells you the total number of orders, in one number.

The example runs all five aggregates over the whole orders table at once: count star for the number of orders, then sum, average, min, and max of amount. With no group by, the entire table is one group, so it returns a single summary row.
